text: 0:19 - the livery on the American Eagle/Envoy regional jet on the left side of the U.S. Airways A320 is American's new livery that was officially revealed by American on January 17th, 2013 (the first aircraft in the new livery being N908NN), whereas the movie chronicles the events of January 15th, 2009. Again at 0:30, we see an American Airlines Boeing 737-823 on the left side of the frame in the new American livery and we also see a United Airlines 737-700 with split scimitar winglets, which weren't installed on 737's until late 2013 and United debuted them on a 737-800 of theirs on Tuesday, February 18th, 2014 on flight 1273 from IAH to LAX. Otherwise, this trailer looks great!

text: This actually looks surprisingly technically correct.  T/O rwy 04 like they did for the actual flight, proper A320 aircraft and flight deck, EPR and N1 rollback with the birdstrikes, First Officer ND/PFD fail after dual engine shutdown, Tom Hanks starting the APU during that cockpit wide view scene, all the caution/warnings and memos on the ECAM, the FAA being dicks.....high hopes for authenticity.   Be interesting to see how they did the flight deck shots. Maybe a greenscreen out the windows as that landscape is definitely movie style CGI rather than typical CAE level FSFD sim visuals.

text: Almost everyone in the comments is saying that is is like flight but with Tom Hanks, but the only similarity is that they both flew planes and did something special, also "Flight" is fiction as in: NOT REAL this however is. Also, some people are saying: "who cares? He only landed in the Hudson River." First of all, if he hadn't landed the plane in the correct way the plane would have cart wheeled and killed every one on board. Second of all, those planes aren't meant to land in water, and third: those people would have frozen to death in the river within fifteen minutes. And I know what your probably thinking if you made it this far into my paragraph: "well doesn't that mean that he was endangering the lives of his passengers that he is sworn to protect?" Yes he is endangering their lives, but at least he isn't endangering even more lives by landing on the streets. I am fourteen and I am still not as naive as some of the "adults" in this comment section. Also flight was total crap.
author: Super Cuttlefish

text: The NTSB can be a it harsh on pilots, like this guy saved a lot of lives with quick thinking. I heard he read accident reports in his freetime to learn from people's mistakes and become a better pilot. He knew the first 10 minutes after rotating of the ground is the most dangerous situation to be in. I'd say a vast majority of plane incidents happen within a half mile to a mile from the airport. I can guarantee he thought about landing in the Hudson hours before the flight, not intentionally, but to be prepared if his engines were to die. You have to make those decisions on the ground so when you're in the air, all you do is put them into play. This man did just that.

text: You know its interesting that they are making MORE out of this then there was...  FAA NEVER went after him saying he could have landed at another airport.   They did simulator testing on that and found,  nearly 50% of the time IF the pilot KNEW what was going on, expected the twin engine failure, and diverted RIGHT after impact they could land at another airfield.   The difference though was 23 seconds.  IF the pilot did ANYTHING including follow a check list and/or try a restart, or anything else.   that was it...  they could not do it.  There was also NEVER a suggestion that one of the engines was still running.   the black boxes showed that right off the bat.  infact 1 thing sully did right away, was a make or break choice that ONLY 20% of tested pilots did.  Without going to the checklist, he immediately turned on his APU.  this one kept his radios and computers going.     face it they are over-dramatizing.  The man was a hero.  Plain and simple.

text: I hope the NTSB doesn't end up getting cast as a straight-up bad guy in this. They did their jobs- investigating all angles- and concluded that the pilots were not at fault. The NTSB is supposed to find out exactly what happened and how to keep it from happening again. If either pilot /were/ responsible, even partially, there would be lessons to draw which might save people in the future. Declining to consider the possibility just because the public was already convinced that Sully was a hero would have been dereliction. I know the movie needs an antagonist of sorts, but if the board is portrayed as some evil conniving government-corporatist force actively trying to railroad the crew it will be disappointing.

text: Even when airline pilots save 155 souls they find themselves being second guessed. It's bad enough that inquiries are tasked with questioning everything, but the news media will feast on your flesh one way or the other so they don't care what it costs you.  When SPLIT SECONDS are all you have, there can be no second-guessing or self-doubt about your abilities and judgement. When my uncle tells us this was a clear example of professional conduct, training, judgement and guts, and the word Miracle slips out . . . . well, he has reasons for a very high bar for those. My family will take his word for it above anyone elses. He has over 50 years in at least 40 different types of aircraft from  piston pounders  to 200 + passenger airliners. He has called every aircraft accident I can remember correctly within hours of finding out simple, basic information.

People so often forget the responsibility a pilot in command has and everyone wants to be the one to tell him what he did wrong.  How about talk about what he did right and how his training kicked in and he made the best practical decision he could come up with at the time of the failures.  No matter how much experience you have in aviation, if you lose both engines at 2800ft ASL I don't care who you are but your probably not going to even consider turning back to the airport, you can waste time doing that, you work with what you have and what he had was the Hudson.

text: To hell with Eastwood, he's nothing but a whiny pro-Trump has-been. Fuck him. Sullenberger was annoying regardless if he asked for all this or not. I remember all the hullabaloo surrounding the incident, this wasn't that long ago. Sullenberger milked his heroism way too long, when to my mind landing a plane safely in the water is more than tough, but it's kinda the goal in being a fucking pilot. A captain should care about their passengers. I mean, a real hero wouldn't call themselves a hero. For all we know, this story could be a lie. Sullenberger could have been a coward and never told the real story? But it's made by white people, so it's okay to be credulous and not question anything. "It's just a movie" Cool, then I should have the freedom to feel it's more jingoist propaganda.  Pilots land planes safely everyday, but everyone feels a plane crashing is never possibility. It is every time you get on one. But the fact it all happened in a sensitive post-9/11 New York makes this even more Heroic American Porn for all the historically uneducated to jerk off to. That's all Sullenberger was to the media, they used his image as a trope, as way to make money and profess how great we are as a nation. Makes me want to puke. This hardly deserves to be a full feature film, as Sullenberger and Eastwood don't have anything real to say other than more patriotic-fetishism nonsense. I get it. Sully did a good thing, great, so did thousands of other Americans. Where's their movie deals? I'm not shit posting, trolling, or whatever. Hate me all you want, this is just my honest opinion.

MAYBE the pilot can resort to his experience and training and save some lives..MAYBE he's able to, amidst the chaos, keep his cool enough to save as many people as he can.... Capt. #SULLY is a HERO... HE may not see himself as such, but I am sure the passengers and family on that "Miracle in the Hudson" flight sure count their blessings when they consider him as the captain and man in charge of that flight.

text: Wait a second. They are making this a blockbuster for the masses, but pilots now are so abused they dont even make enough money to pay off the debts of their schooling. Pilots have to take second jobs as store clerks to pay their bills. A pilots wife HAS to have a job, her husband cannot keep her to be a full time stay at home mother to his children on a pilots wage! No chance! No pilots ever want their own sons or daughters because of how shit it has become as a career now. And Sully himself tried to raise awareness of this (while he had the keys to the city of NY and was the medias "hero"), only to be silenced by that same media instantly.  BUT NOW they make a movie, showing him a hero again.  What about his message? What about the changes he wants? What about that, then?  Fucking hypocritical society of the West, huh? What a joke.

This is not "dramatic license". This is an assassination of multiple crucial truths,  and the deliberate warping of the very fabric of the story which is purported to be told.  This is a public fraud and it is unconscionable IRL and in "Art" and in every in-between.

text: This is a very realistic recreation of the "miracle on the Hudson" plane "crash" and Tom Hanks' portrayal of Captain Chesley "Sully" Sullenberger is probably one of the best parts I've ever seen him play due to his uncanny resemblance to the real hero pilot of that incident.  Much of the plot of the film revolves around the NTSB investigators suggesting that Sully was not a good pilot because he decided to splash down in the Hudson instead of turning around for a landing back at LaGuardia airport or flying over the Teterboro airport in New Jersey.  Such a ruling would have forced him to take early retirement and lose his license to fly commercial airliners. They had computer simulations that "proved" that such an emergency landing could be easily done assuming he had a partially functional left engine.  Things looked bad for Scully for a while, but then some facts emerged that the NTSB had been conveniently concealing.  I don't want to spoil this excellent film by revealing them.  But, I'll just say this.  If you are ever on a airliner when all of the engines fail at once, you'll be glad to have Scully at the controls!

text: This is EXTREMELY inaccurate. US Airways 1549 occurred January 15 2009. The planes in the beginning are not from 2009. United Airlines DID NOT have the globe livery until 2010 when they (unfortunately) merged with Continental airlines. These two United planes should have continental written on the side of it. Yes they did fix this in the movie, BUT IT WAS STILL WRONG! Continental never had any ERJ 170s! They labeled the plane in the movie, Continental Connection, but continental connection only had a fleet of ATRâ€™s and Q400â€™s (which one had been involved in Colgan Air 3407 [N200WQ]). The second huge mistake was also the American Airlines planes. THE LIVERY THEY WERE WEARING WAS FROM 2013-PRESENT! In 2009 they still wore the Chrome Livery of the silver paint! Everything at LaGuardia is screwed up in the movie. They somehow got the delta planes correct. (Except back then Delta Airlines was going through new livery repaints since 2008. So it would be unrealistic to see no Delta Airlines 2000s colors in the â€œDeltaflotâ€ livery. They could have done a MUCH better job with this movie.
